---
import BaseLayout from '../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';

const breadcrumbSchema = {
  '@context': 'https://schema.org',
  '@type': 'BreadcrumbList',
  itemListElement: [
    { '@type': 'ListItem', position: 1, name: 'Home', item: 'https://ultrazoom.app/' },
    { '@type': 'ListItem', position: 2, name: 'Compare', item: 'https://ultrazoom.app/compare' },
    { '@type': 'ListItem', position: 3, name: 'Ultra Zoom vs. Chrome built-in zoom', item: 'https://ultrazoom.app/compare/chrome-built-in-zoom' },
  ],
};

const faqSchema = {
  '@context': 'https://schema.org',
  '@type': 'FAQPage',
  mainEntity: [
    {
      '@type': 'Question',
      name: 'Why is the built-in Chrome zoom blurry on images?',
      acceptedAnswer: {
        '@type': 'Answer',
        text: 'Chrome\'s Ctrl+= zoom scales the rendered page — including the image element on screen. The image data itself is whatever resolution the page served, usually a thumbnail. Hover-to-zoom extensions like Ultra Zoom load the full-resolution source image directly, so what you see is sharp instead of upscaled.',
      },
    },
    {
      '@type': 'Question',
      name: 'Can Chrome show full-resolution images natively?',
      acceptedAnswer: {
        '@type': 'Answer',
        text: 'Only by right-clicking and choosing Open Image in New Tab — and only if the page actually links to the full-resolution file. Most modern sites serve responsive thumbnails, so even that workflow shows you the optimized version, not the source.',
      },
    },
    {
      '@type': 'Question',
      name: 'Is Ultra Zoom safe to install?',
      acceptedAnswer: {
        '@type': 'Answer',
        text: 'Ultra Zoom has zero telemetry by design — no analytics endpoint, no remote code, no server that sees your browsing. Read the architecture write-up for the full breakdown.',
      },
    },
  ],
};
---

<BaseLayout
  title="Ultra Zoom vs. Chrome Built-in Zoom — Why Hover-to-Zoom Wins on Images"
  description="Chrome's Ctrl+= zooms the page; Ultra Zoom loads the full-resolution source image. Here is why hover-to-zoom looks sharp and built-in zoom looks blurry on image-heavy sites."
  currentPage="compare"
  og={{
    url: 'https://ultrazoom.app/compare/chrome-built-in-zoom',
    title: 'Ultra Zoom vs. Chrome built-in zoom',
    description: 'Why hover-to-zoom hits the source image and Ctrl+= shows you an upscaled thumbnail.',
    image: 'https://ultrazoom.app/og/compare-chrome-built-in-zoom.png',
    imageWidth: 1200,
    imageHeight: 630,
  }}
  jsonLd={[breadcrumbSchema, faqSchema]}
>
    <main class="main page-content" id="main-content">
        <h1>Ultra Zoom vs. Chrome built-in zoom</h1>

        <p class="pricing-intro">Chrome has zoom built in &mdash; Ctrl+= or pinch on a trackpad. So why install a hover-zoom extension? Because the two do completely different things, and on image-heavy sites the difference is whether you see the source photo or an upscaled thumbnail.</p>

        <section class="help-section" id="how-each-works">
            <h2>How each one actually works</h2>
            <ul class="help-list">
                <li><strong>Chrome built-in zoom</strong> &mdash; scales the rendered page. The image element on screen gets bigger; the underlying image data does not change. If the page served you a 400&times;300 thumbnail, that&rsquo;s still what&rsquo;s being scaled. <a href="/blog/native-browser-image-zoom">Read the deep dive</a>.</li>
                <li><strong>Ultra Zoom</strong> &mdash; hover an image and the extension fetches the <em>full-resolution source</em> directly from the host (not the thumbnail), then shows it as an overlay at native resolution. The result is sharp, not upscaled.</li>
            </ul>
        </section>

        <section class="help-section" id="when-it-matters">
            <h2>When it matters</h2>
            <ul class="help-list">
                <li><strong>Real estate listings.</strong> MLS sites serve compressed thumbnails on the listing page. The full-resolution gallery photo is one network request away &mdash; Ultra Zoom makes it one hover.</li>
                <li><strong>Online shopping.</strong> Amazon, eBay, Etsy and Shopify stores serve responsive image variants. Hover-zoom shows you the high-res source so you can see fabric texture, stitching, scratches.</li>
                <li><strong>Auctions and collectibles.</strong> Eyeballing condition on coin and watch listings only works at native resolution.</li>
                <li><strong>Reading on Reddit, Tumblr, Twitter/X, Pinterest.</strong> Each one has a different preview-vs-original story; Ultra Zoom standardises it.</li>
            </ul>
        </section>

        <section class="help-section" id="feature-parity">
            <h2>Side by side</h2>
            <div class="pricing-compare-wrap">
                <table class="pricing-compare">
                    <thead>
                        <tr>
                            <th scope="col">Feature</th>
                            <th scope="col">Chrome built-in zoom</th>
                            <th scope="col">Ultra Zoom</th>
                        </tr>
                    </thead>
                    <tbody>
                        <tr>
                            <th scope="row">Loads full-resolution source image</th>
                            <td aria-label="Not included">&ndash;</td>
                            <td aria-label="Included">&#10003;</td>
                        </tr>
                        <tr>
                            <th scope="row">Site-specific image plugins</th>
                            <td aria-label="Not included">&ndash;</td>
                            <td aria-label="Included">&#10003;</td>
                        </tr>
                        <tr>
                            <th scope="row">Hover preview without click or reflow</th>
                            <td aria-label="Not included">&ndash;</td>
                            <td aria-label="Included">&#10003;</td>
                        </tr>
                        <tr>
                            <th scope="row">Theater mode &amp; gallery navigation</th>
                            <td aria-label="Not included">&ndash;</td>
                            <td aria-label="Included">&#10003;</td>
                        </tr>
                        <tr>
                            <th scope="row">Reverse image search shortcuts</th>
                            <td aria-label="Not included">&ndash;</td>
                            <td aria-label="Included">&#10003;</td>
                        </tr>
                        <tr>
                            <th scope="row">On-device AI upscaling</th>
                            <td aria-label="Not included">&ndash;</td>
                            <td aria-label="Included">&#10003; (Pro)</td>
                        </tr>
                        <tr>
                            <th scope="row">Per-site page zoom level</th>
                            <td aria-label="Included">&#10003;</td>
                            <td aria-label="Not included">&ndash;</td>
                        </tr>
                        <tr>
                            <th scope="row">Zero telemetry</th>
                            <td aria-label="Included">&#10003;</td>
                            <td aria-label="Included">&#10003;</td>
                        </tr>
                    </tbody>
                </table>
            </div>
        </section>

        <section class="help-section" id="cta">
            <h2>Try it free</h2>
            <p>The core extension is free forever, with the entire site catalogue. Pro is a 7-day free trial when you&rsquo;re ready &mdash; <a href="/pricing">see plans</a>.</p>
            <ul class="install-links">
                <li>
                    <a href="https://chromewebstore.google.com/detail/ultra-zoom/jalclpdejbeamaamcpbolkclpnleagmg" class="install-button chrome" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Install for Chrome</a>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <a href="https://addons.mozilla.org/en-US/firefox/addon/ultra-zoom/" class="install-button firefox" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Install for Firefox</a>
                </li>
            </ul>
        </section>
    </main>
</BaseLayout>
